For two [[Definition:Set|sets]] to be [[Definition:Set Equivalence|equivalent]], there needs to exist a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]] between them.\nIn the following, let $\phi$, $\phi_1$, $\phi_2$ etc. be understood to be [[Definition:Bijection|bijections]].\n=== Reflexive ===\nFrom [[Identity Mapping is Bijection]], the [[Definition:Identity Mapping|identity mapping]] $I_S: S \to S$ is the required [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]].\nThus there exists a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]] from $S$ to itself and $S$ is therefore equivalent to itself.\nTherefore [[Definition:Set Equivalence|set equivalence]] is [[Definition:Reflexive Relation|reflexive]].\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Symmetric ===
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
| r = S \sim T
| c =
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \exists \phi: S \to T
| c = {{Defof|Set Equivalence}}
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \exists \phi^{-1}: T \to S
| c = [[Bijection iff Inverse is Bijection]]
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = T \sim S
| c = {{Defof|Set Equivalence}}: $\phi^{-1}$ is also a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]]
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nTherefore [[Definition:Set Equivalence|set equivalence]] is [[Definition:Symmetric Relation|symmetric]].\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Transitive ===
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
| r = S_1 \sim S_2 \land S_2 \sim S_3
| c =
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \exists \phi_1: S_1 \to S_2 \land \exists \phi_2: S_2 \to S_3
| c = {{Defof|Set Equivalence}}
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \exists \phi_2 \circ \phi_1: S_1 \to S_3
| c = [[Composite of Bijections is Bijection]]: $\phi_2 \circ \phi_1$ is a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]]
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = S_1 \sim S_3
| c = {{Defof|Set Equivalence}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nTherefore [[Definition:Set Equivalence|set equivalence]] is [[Definition:Transitive Relation|transitive]].\n{{qed}}
{{expand|See talk}}

