Let $\mathbb S$ be a [[Definition:Set Partition|partition]] of $S$.\nFrom [[Definition:Relation Induced by Partition|Relation Induced by Partition]], we define the [[Definition:Relation|relation]] $\RR$ on $S$ by:
:$\RR = \set {\tuple {x, y}: \paren {\exists T \in \mathbb S: x \in T \land y \in T} }$\n=== Test for Equivalence ===\nWe are to show that $\RR$ is an [[Definition:Equivalence Relation|equivalence relation]].\nChecking in turn each of the critera for [[Definition:Equivalence Relation|equivalence]]:\n==== Reflexive ====
$\RR$ is [[Definition:Reflexive Relation|reflexive]]:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
| r = \paren {x \in T \land x \in T}
| c = [[Rule of Idempotence]]
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadstoandfrom
| r = \tuple {x, x} \in \RR
| c = Definition of $\RR$
}}
{{end-eqn}}\n{{qed|lemma}}\n==== Symmetric ====
$\RR$ is [[Definition:Symmetric Relation|symmetric]]:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
| r = \tuple {x, y} \in \RR
| c =
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = x \in T \land y \in T
| c = Definition of $\RR$
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = y \in T \land x \in T
| c = [[Rule of Commutation]]
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \tuple {y, x} \in \RR
| c = Definition of $\RR$
}}
{{end-eqn}}\n{{qed|lemma}}\n==== Transitive ====
$\RR$ is [[Definition:Transitive Relation|transitive]]:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = x \in T \land y \in T
| o = \leadstoandfrom
| r = \tuple {x, y} \in \RR
| c = Definition of $\RR$
}}\n{{eqn | l = y \in T \land z \in T
| o = \leadstoandfrom
| r = \tuple {y, z} \in \RR
| c = Definition of $\RR$
}}\n{{eqn | l = \paren {x \in T \land y \in T} \land \paren {y \in T \land z \in T}
| o = \leadstoandfrom
| r = \tuple {x, z} \in \RR
| c = Definition of $\RR$
}}
{{end-eqn}}\n{{qed|lemma}}\nSo $\RR$ is [[Definition:Reflexive Relation|reflexive]], [[Definition:Symmetric Relation|symmetric]] and [[Definition:Transitive Relation|transitive]].\nHence, by definition, $\RR$ is an [[Definition:Equivalence Relation|equivalence relation]].\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Test for Uniqueness ===\nNow by definition of a [[Definition:Set Partition|partition]], we have that:
:$\mathbb S$ [[Definition:Set Partition|partition]]s $S \implies \forall x \in S: \exists T \in \mathbb S: x \in T$\nAlso:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = x, y \in T
| o = \leadsto
| r = \tuple {x, y} \in \RR
| c = Definition of $\RR$
}}\n{{eqn | l = x \in T_1, y \in T_2, T_1 \ne T_2
| o = \leadsto
| r = \tuple{x, y} \notin \RR
| c = {{Defof|Set Partition}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nThus $\mathbb S$ is the [[Definition:Set of Sets|set]] of [[Definition:Equivalence Class|$\RR$-classes]] constructed above, and no other [[Definition:Relation|relation]] can be constructed in this way.\n{{qed}}

