solution:
=== Necessary Condition ===\nSuppose $f$ is [[Definition:Differentiable Real Function at Point|differentiable]] at $c$.\nThen by definition $f' \left({c}\right)$ exists.\nSo we can define $\varphi$ by:
:$\varphi \left({x}\right) = \begin{cases}
\dfrac {f \left({x}\right) - f \left({c}\right)} {x - c} & : x \ne c, x \in I

f' \left({c}\right) & : x = c
\end{cases}$\nCondition $(2)$, that $\varphi$ is [[Definition:Continuous Real Function at Point|continuous]] at $c$, is satisfied, since:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \varphi \left({c}\right)
| r = f' \left({c}\right)
| c = Definition of $\varphi$
}}\n{{eqn | r = \lim_{x \to c} \frac {f \left({x}\right) - f \left({c}\right)} {x - c}
| c = Definition of [[Definition:Derivative|derivative]]
}}\n{{eqn | r = \lim_{x \to c} \varphi \left({x}\right)
| c = Definition of $\varphi$
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nFinally, condition $(1)$ is vacuous for $x = c$.\nFor $x \ne c$, it follows from the definition of $\varphi$ by dividing both sides of $(1)$ by $x - c$.\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Sufficient Condition ===\nSuppose a $\varphi$ as in the theorem statement exists.\nThen for $x \ne c$, we have that:
:$\varphi \left({x}\right) = \dfrac {f \left({x}\right) - f \left({c}\right)} {x - c}$\nSince $\varphi$ is [[Definition:Continuous Real Function at Point|continuous]] at $c$:
:$\displaystyle \varphi \left({c}\right) = \lim_{x \to c} \varphi \left({x}\right) = \lim_{x \to c} \frac {f \left({x}\right) - f \left({c}\right)} {x - c}$\nThat is, $f$ is [[Definition:Differentiable Real Function at Point|differentiable]] at $c$, and $f' \left({c}\right) = \varphi \left({c}\right)$.\n{{qed}}
{{Namedfor|Constantin Carathéodory|cat = Carathéodory}}
[[Category:Direct Proofs]]
[[Category:Real Analysis]]
[[Category:Differential Calculus]]
