First we show that:
:$\tuple {x, y} \notin \RR \implies \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR = \O$\nSuppose two $\RR$-classes are ''not'' [[Definition:Disjoint Sets|disjoint]]:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR \ne \O
| o = \leadsto
| r = \exists z: z \in \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR
| c = {{Defof|Empty Set}}
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \exists z: z \in \eqclass x \RR \land z \in \eqclass y \RR
| c = {{Defof|Set Intersection}}
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \exists z: \paren {\tuple {x, z} \in \RR} \land \paren {\tuple {y, z} \in \RR}
| c = {{Defof|Equivalence Class}}
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \exists z: \paren {\tuple {x, z} \in \RR} \land \paren {\tuple {x, y} \in \RR}
| c = {{Defof|Symmetric Relation}}: $\RR$ is symmetric
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = \tuple {x, y} \in \RR
| c = {{Defof|Transitive Relation}}: $\RR$ is transitive
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nThus we have shown that $\eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR \ne \O \implies \tuple {x, y} \in \RR$.\nTherefore, by the [[Rule of Transposition]]:
:$\tuple {x, y} \notin \RR \implies \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR = \O$\nNow we show that:
:$\eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR = \O \implies \tuple {x, y} \notin \RR$\nSuppose $\tuple {x, y} \in \RR$.
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | o =
| r = y \in \eqclass y \RR
| c = {{Defof|Equivalence Class}}
}}\n{{eqn | o =
| r = \tuple {x, y} \in \RR
| c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|by hypothesis]]
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = y \in \eqclass x \RR
| c = {{Defof|Equivalence Class}}
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
| r = y \in \eqclass x \RR \land y \in \eqclass y \RR
| c = [[Rule of Conjunction]]
}}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto
