Let $S, T$ be [[Definition:Set|sets]].\nLet $\powerset S, \powerset T$ denote their [[Definition:Power Set|power sets]].\nLet $f: S \to T$ and $g: T \to S$ be [[Definition:Injection|injections]] that we know to exist between $S$ and $T$.\nConsider the [[Definition:Relative Complement|relative complements]] of elements of $\powerset S$ and $\powerset T$ as [[Definition:Mapping|mappings]]:
:$\complement_S: \powerset S \to \powerset S: \forall X \in \powerset S: \relcomp S X = S \setminus X$
:$\complement_T: \powerset T \to \powerset T: \forall Y \in \powerset T: \relcomp T Y = T \setminus Y$
which follow directly from the definition of [[Definition:Relative Complement|relative complement]].\nLet $\alpha$ and $\beta$ denote the [[Definition:Direct Image Mapping of Mapping|direct image mappings]] of $f$ and $g$, respectively.\nConsider the [[Definition:Mapping|mapping]] $z: \powerset S \to \powerset S$ defined by the [[Definition:Composite Mapping|composition]]:
:$z = \complement_S \circ \beta \circ \complement_T \circ \alpha$\n=== $z$ is an increasing mapping ===\nLet $A, B \in \powerset S$ with $A \subseteq B$.\nWe have:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \map \alpha A
| o = \subseteq
| r = \map \alpha B
| c = [[Image of Subset under Relation is Subset of Image/Corollary 2|Image of Subset under Relation is Subset of Image: Corollary 2]]
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \map {\paren {\complement_T \circ \alpha} } A
| o = \supseteq
| r = \map {\paren {\complement_T \circ \alpha} } B
| c = [[Set Complement inverts Subsets]]
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \map {\paren {\beta \circ \complement_T \circ \alpha} } A
| o = \supseteq
| r = \map {\paren {\beta \circ \complement_T \circ \alpha} } B
| c = [[Image of Subset under Relation is Subset of Image/Corollary 2|Image of Subset under Relation is Subset of Image: Corollary 2]]
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \map {\paren {\complement_S \circ \beta \circ \complement_T \circ \alpha} } A
| o = \subseteq
| r = \map {\paren {\complement_S \circ \beta \circ \complement_T \circ \alpha} } B
| c = [[Set Complement inverts Subsets]]
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \map z A
| o = \subseteq
| r = \map z B
| c = Definition of $z$
}}
{{end-eqn}}\n{{qed|lemma}}\nBy the [[Knaster-Tarski Lemma/Power Set|Knaster-Tarski Lemma: Power Set]], there is a $\mathbb G \in \powerset S$ such that:
:$\map z {\mathbb G} = \mathbb G$\nFrom [[Relative Complement of Relative Complement]] we have that $\complement_S \circ \complement_S$ is the [[Definition:Identity Mapping|identity mapping]] on $\powerset S$.\nThus we obtain:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \relcomp S {\mathbb G}
| r = \map {\paren {\complement_S \circ z} } {\mathbb G}
| c =
}}\n{{eqn | r = \map {\paren {\complement_S \circ \complement_S \circ \beta \circ \complement_T \circ \alpha} } {\mathbb G}
| c = Definition of $z$
}}\n{{eqn | r = g \sqbrk {\map {\paren {\complement_T \circ \alpha} } {\mathbb G} }
| c = as $\complement_S \circ \complement_S = I_{\powerset S}$
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nAt this stage, a diagram can be helpful:
:[[File:Cantor-Bernstein-Schroeder.png|500px]]\nLet $h: S \to T$ be the [[Definition:Mapping|mapping]] defined as:
:$\forall x \in S: \map h x = \begin {cases}
\map f x & : x \in \mathbb G

\map {g^{-1} } x & : x \in \relcomp S {\mathbb G}
\end {cases}$\nFrom the above, we have that:
:$\relcomp S {\mathbb G} \subseteq g \sqbrk T$\nTherefore, as $g$ is an [[Definition:Injection|injection]], it follows that the [[Definition:Preimage of Element under Mapping|preimage]] $\map {g^{-1} } x$ is a [[Definition:Singleton|singleton]].\nSo $h$ is a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]] by dint of the [[Definition:Injection|injective]] nature of both $f$ and $g^{-1}$.\n{{qed}}

