From [[Set Difference and Intersection form Partition]]:
: $\paren {R \setminus S} \cup \paren {R \cap S} = R = \paren {R \setminus T} \cup \paren {R \cap T}$
: $\paren {R \cap S} \cap \paren {R \setminus S} = \O = \paren {R \cap T} \cap \paren {R \setminus T}$
whatever $R, S, T$ might be.\nLet $R \setminus S = R \setminus T$.\nThen:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \paren {\paren {R \setminus S} \cup \paren {R \cap S} } \setminus \paren {R \setminus S}
| r = \paren {\paren {R \setminus T} \cup \paren {R \cap T} } \setminus \paren {R \setminus T}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \paren {R \cap S} \setminus \paren {R \setminus S}
| r = \paren {R \cap T} \setminus \paren {R \setminus T}
| c = [[Set Difference with Union is Set Difference]]
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nNow, we have from [[Set Difference with Disjoint Set]]:
:$S \cap T = \O \iff S \setminus T = S$
and so:
:$\paren {R \cap S} \setminus \paren {R \setminus S} = R \cap S$
and:
:$\paren {R \cap T} \setminus \paren {R \setminus T} = R \cap T$\nSo:
:$R \cap S = R \cap T$\nWe can use exactly the same reasoning if we assume $R \cap S = R \cap T$:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \paren {\paren {R \setminus S} \cup \paren {R \cap S} } \setminus \paren {R \cap S}
| r = \paren {\paren {R \setminus T} \cup \paren {R \cap T} } \setminus \paren {R \cap T}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \paren {R \setminus S} \setminus \paren {R \cap S}
| r = \paren {R \setminus T} \setminus \paren {R \cap T}
| c = [[Set Difference with Union is Set Difference]]
}}
{{end-eqn}}
and then because of [[Set Difference with Disjoint Set]] as above:
:$\paren {R \setminus S} \setminus \paren {R \cap S} = R \setminus S$
and:
:$\paren {R \setminus T} \setminus \paren {R \cap T} = R \setminus T$\nSo:
:$R \setminus S = R \setminus T$\n{{qed}}

