Let $\tuple {x, y} \in \paren {S_1 \times S_2} \setminus \paren {T_1 \times T_2}$.\nThen:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \tuple {x, y} \in S_1 \times S_2
| o = \land
| r = \tuple {x, y} \notin T_1 \times T_2
| c = {{Defof|Set Difference}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadstoandfrom
| l = x \in S_1 \land y \in S_2
| o = \land
| r = \neg \paren {x \in T_1 \land y \in T_2}
| c = {{Defof|Cartesian Product}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadstoandfrom
| l = x \in S_1 \land y \in S_2
| o = \land
| r = \paren {x \notin T_1 \lor y \notin T_2}
| c = [[De Morgan's Laws (Logic)/Disjunction of Negations|De Morgan's Laws: Disjunction of Negations]]
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadstoandfrom
| l = \paren {x \in S_1 \land y \in S_2 \land x \notin T_1}
| o = \lor
| r = \paren {x \in S_1 \land y \in S_2 \land y \notin T_2}
| c = [[Rule of Distribution]]
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadstoandfrom
| l = \paren {x \in S_1 \setminus T_1 \land y \in S_2}
| o = \lor
| r = \paren {x \in S_1 \land y \in S_2 \setminus T_2}
| c = {{Defof|Set Difference}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadstoandfrom
| l = \paren {\tuple {x, y} \in \paren {S_1 \setminus T_1} \times S_2}
| o = \lor
| r = \paren {\tuple {x, y} \in S_1 \times \paren {S_2 \setminus T_2} }
| c = {{Defof|Cartesian Product}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadstoandfrom
| l = \tuple {x, y}
| o = \in
| r = \paren {S_1 \times \paren {S_2 \setminus T_2} } \cup \paren {\paren {S_1 \setminus T_1} \times S_2}
| c = {{Defof|Set Union}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nThe result follows from the definition of [[Definition:Subset|subset]] and [[Definition:Set Equality|set equality]].\n{{qed}}

