=== Sufficient Condition ===\nSuppose that:
:$\forall S_1, S_2 \subseteq S: \RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2} = \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}$\nIf $S$ is [[Definition:Singleton|singleton]], the result follows immediately as $\RR$ would ''have'' to be [[Definition:One-to-Many Relation|one-to-many]].\nSo, assume $S$ is not [[Definition:Singleton|singleton]].\nSuppose $\RR$ is specifically ''not'' [[Definition:One-to-Many Relation|one-to-many]].\nSo:
:$\exists x, y \in S: \exists z \in T: \tuple {x, z} \in T, \tuple {y, z} \in T, x \ne y$
and of course $\set x \subseteq S, \set y \subseteq S$.\nSo:
:$z \in \RR \sqbrk {\set x}$
:$z \in \RR \sqbrk {\set y}$
and so by definition of [[Definition:Set Intersection|intersection]]:
:$z \in \RR \sqbrk {\set x} \cap \RR \sqbrk {\set y}$\nBut:
:$\set x \cap \set y = \O$\nThus from [[Image of Empty Set is Empty Set]]:
:$\RR \sqbrk {\set x \cap \set y} = \O$
and so:
:$\RR \sqbrk {\set x \cap \set y} \ne \RR \sqbrk {\set x} \cap \RR \sqbrk {\set y}$\n{{qed|lemma}}\n=== Necessary Condition ===\nLet $\RR$ be [[Definition:One-to-Many Relation|one-to-many]].\nFrom [[Image of Intersection under Relation]], we already have:
:$\RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2} \subseteq \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}$\nSo we just need to show:
:$\RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2} \subseteq \RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2}$\nLet $t \in \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}$.\nThen:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = t
| o = \in
| r = \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}
| c =
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = t
| o = \in
| r = \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \land t \in \RR \sqbrk {S_2}
| c = {{Defof|Set Intersection}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \exists s_1 \in S_1: \tuple {s_1, t}
| o = \in
| r = \RR \land \exists s_2 \in S_2: \tuple {s_2, t} \in \RR
| c = {{Defof|Relation}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = s_1
| r = s_2
| c = {{Defof|One-to-Many Relation}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = s_1 = s_2
| o = \in
| r = S_1 \land s_1 = s_2 \in S_2
| c =
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = s_1 = s_2
| o = \in
| r = S_1 \cap S_2
| c = {{Defof|Set Intersection}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \map \RR {s_1} = \map \RR {s_2}
| o = \in
| r = \RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2}
| c = [[Image of Element is Subset]]
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}
| o = \subseteq
| r = \RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2}
| c = {{Defof|Subset}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nSo if $\RR$ is [[Definition:One-to-Many Relation|one-to-many]], it follows that:
:$\RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2} = \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}$\n{{qed|lemma}}\nPutting the results together, we see that:
:$\RR \sqbrk {S_1 \cap S_2} = \RR \sqbrk {S_1} \cap \RR \sqbrk {S_2}$ {{iff}} $\RR$ is [[Definition:One-to-Many Relation|one-to-many]].\n{{qed}}
[[Category:Relation Theory]]
[[Category:Set Intersection]]
