solution:
Let $f: S \to T$ be a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]].\nFrom [[Inverse of Bijection is Bijection]], $f^{-1}$ is also a [[Definition:Bijection|bijection]].\nLet $x \in S$.\nFrom [[Inverse Element of Bijection]]:
:$\exists y \in T: y = \map f x \implies x = \map {f^{-1} } y$\nThen:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \map {f^{-1} \circ f} x
| r = \map {f^{-1} } {\map f x}
| c = {{Defof|Composition of Mappings}}
}}\n{{eqn | r = \map {f^{-1} } y
| c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|By Hypothesis]]
}}\n{{eqn | r = x
| c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|By Hypothesis]]
}}\n{{eqn | r = \map {I_S} x
| c = {{Defof|Identity Mapping}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nFrom [[Domain of Composite Relation]] and [[Codomain of Composite Relation]], the [[Definition:Domain of Mapping|domain]] and [[Definition:Codomain of Mapping|codomain]] of $f^{-1} \circ f$ are both $S$, and so are those of $I_S$ by [[Definition:Identity Mapping|definition]].\nSo all the criteria for [[Equality of Mappings]] are met and thus $f^{-1} \circ f = I_S$.\nLet $y \in T$.\nFrom [[Inverse Element of Bijection]]:
:$\exists x \in S: x = \map {f^{-1} } y \implies y = \map f x$\nThen:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \map {f \circ f^{-1} } y
| r = \map f {\map {f^{-1} } y}
| c = {{Defof|Composition of Mappings}}
}}\n{{eqn | r = \map f x
| c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|By Hypothesis]]
}}\n{{eqn | r = y
| c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|By Hypothesis]]
}}\n{{eqn | r = \map {I_T} y
| c = {{Defof|Identity Mapping}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nFrom [[Domain of Composite Relation]] and [[Codomain of Composite Relation]], the [[Definition:Domain of Mapping|domain]] and [[Definition:Codomain of Mapping|codomain]] of $f \circ f^{-1}$ are both $T$, and so are those of $I_T$ by [[Definition:Identity Mapping|definition]].\nSo all the criteria for [[Equality of Mappings]] are met and thus $f \circ f^{-1} = I_T$.
{{Qed}}

