solution:
Suppose $\map {b_n} x \ge \map {b_{n + 1} } x$ for each $x \in D$.\nAll we need to show is that:
:$\displaystyle \sum_{n \mathop = 1}^\infty \size {\map {b_n} x - \map {b_{n + 1} } x}$
[[Definition:Uniform Convergence|converges uniformly]] on $D$.
{{explain|Why is the above sufficient?

On the surface of it, no reference has been made to $\map {a_n} x$.

Its connection to the above statement needs to be clarified.}}\nTo do this we show that the [[Definition:Cauchy Criterion for Sequences|Cauchy criterion]] holds.\nAssign $\epsilon < 0$.\nThen by definition of [[Definition:Uniform Convergence|uniform convergence]]:
:$\displaystyle \exists N \in \N: \forall x \in D: \forall n \ge N: \size {\map {b_n} x} < \frac \epsilon 2$\nLet $x \in D$ and $n > m \ge N$.\nThen:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \sum_{k \mathop = m + 1}^n \size {\map {b_k} x - \map {b_{k + 1} } x}
| r = \sum_{k \mathop = m + 1}^n \paren {\map {b_k} x - \map {b_{k + 1} } x}
}}\n{{eqn | r = \map {b_{m + 1} } x - \map {b_{n + 1} } x
}}\n{{eqn | r = \size {\map {b_{m + 1} } x - \map {b_{n + 1} } x}
}}\n{{eqn | o = \le
| r = \size {\map {b_{m + 1} } x + \map {b_{n + 1} } x}
}}\n{{eqn | o = <
| r = \frac \epsilon 2 + \frac \epsilon 2
}}\n{{eqn | r = \epsilon
}}
{{end-eqn}}\n{{qed}}
{{Namedfor|Johann Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet|cat = Dirichlet}}

